Linxpad is a fullscreen application launcher and organizer for Linux inspired by the macOS experience.

It works on both X11 and Wayland and integrates with any desktop environment or window manager.

KDE, XFCE, LXDE or tiling window managers like Sway, Hyprland, i3, and Openbox.

You can launch Linxpad from your panel… or with a keyboard shortcut.

It supports both mouse and keyboard navigation… so you can work the way you prefer.

On first launch… Linxpad automatically scans your system… and organizes your applications into pages.

At the bottom… dots indicate the available pages.

Click to switch… or use the page-up and page-down keys.

Within each page… you can use the arrow keys to move between applications and use enter to launch them.

Rearranging apps is simple.

Just drag and drop.

Drag one icon onto another… to create a folder.

The folder name appears at the top left.

Click it to rename it.

Press Escape… or click on an empty area to return to the main view.






Drag applications into folders to organize them.

Drag them out… to remove them.

To create a new page… drag an icon to the far right… of the last page.

You can also move applications between pages… by dragging them to the edges of the screen.

Start typing… to search instantly.

Linxpad shows results from your applications… your home folder… and the web.

Use the arrow keys… to navigate results.

Press Enter… to launch.

